{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"659"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/659"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.03,0.15,0.64,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/659"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"659"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52804"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4230"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9103"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of colicky abdominal pain, distension and vomiting. He has otherwise been well recently and works as a farmer. He has a medical history of various skin lesions treated including a squamous cell carcinoma and a melanoma excised by his General Practitioner. He takes no regular medications. On abdominal examination, his abdomen is distended and soft and frequent high-pitched bowel sounds can be heard. There are no other abnormal findings. A CT scan shows multiple dilated loops of small bowel, proximal to an obstructing mass lesion in the mid-jejunal region.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A Peutz-Jegher-associated tumour","Lymphoma","Primary adenocarcinoma","Metastatic melanoma","Crohn\u0027s disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has small bowel obstruction. Most cases of small bowel obstruction are either due to adhesions or an abdominal wall hernia. In this instance, the patient has not had any previous abdominal surgery, so adhesions are unlikely. He does not have any obvious hernias and the radiological finding of a mass suggests an unusual cause for the obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmall bowel tumours are not common. The usual primary tumours that occur in this part of the gut are either \u003Cstrong\u003Eadenocarcinomas\u003C/strong\u003E, neuroendocrine tumours, sarcomas or \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphomas\u003C/strong\u003E. However, the most common neoplastic tumours found in the small intestine are metastatic deposits. Any of the conditions described could present in such a way. Tumours in the small bowel typically present when they are of sufficient size to cause luminal obstruction. They may not cause any other symptoms until that acute event. Another, but less common, way they may present is at the apex of an intussusception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the picture of a man living in the country which has one of the highest rates of melanoma globally and with a history of removal of sun-related skin lesions, the likelihood of \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E must be high. Melanoma can metastasise to any part of the body, the small bowel being a well-recognised site. His initial tumour may have been inadequately excised, or the patient may have developed another, unrecognised, primary tumour. It is not uncommon for melanomas to present with metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the absence of any pre-existing symptoms, \u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn\u0027s disease \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be down the list of differential diagnoses. The \u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jegher\u003C/strong\u003E syndrome is associated with small bowel polyps and if large enough, they could cause intestinal obstruction. However this syndrome is a rare disorder and this patient\u0027s problem is much more likely to be related to metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metastatic melanoma should always be considered in any patient who develops a new set of symptoms on the background of a previous melanoma excision."],"references":["Reynolds I, Healy P, McNamara DA. Malignant tumours of the small intestine. Surgeon. 2014;12:263-70. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24637026/","Pourmand K, Itzkowitz SH. Small Bowel Neoplasms and Polyps. Currently Gastroenterol Rep 2016;18:23. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27086004/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52804"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"659"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52804"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T23:08:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-29T07:10:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"659"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},